    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "An intermittent sound coming from under the handle might indicate an issue beyond just a clogged washer. It's possible that the water supply line has a partial obstruction or there's an issue with the aerator or shut-off valve. Here are a couple of additional steps you can take:\n\n1. Shut off the water supply, remove the aerator (it's usually a cap at the base of the sink), and check inside for any debris or obstructions that could be causing the sputtering sound.\n2. After cleaning the aerator, turn the water supply back on and observe if the sound persists.\n3. If it does, inspect the shut-off valve beneath the sink for any sediment buildup or improper sealing that may be preventing water from flowing smoothly and producing a whooshing sound.\n4. Apply some plumber's grease to the valve seat to improve the seal if needed. If the precious sounds continue to manifest, the issue could be with the water line closer to the main valve, possibly leading to a slight blockage or fissure. Given your level of comfort, you might consider reaching out to a plumber, especially since it sounds like it could be something less convenient for DIY repairs.",
